<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  F1-10 — hardened runtime entitlements (design §6.3).

  `hardenedRuntime: true` is required for notarisation, and the hardened runtime
  is precisely what makes these two entitlements necessary: it blocks writable-
  executable memory by default, and V8 is a JIT. Without them the app is signed,
  notarised, and crashes on launch — which is the worst possible failure mode,
  because every check in the pipeline passes.

    allow-jit                        V8 needs MAP_JIT pages.
    allow-unsigned-executable-memory V8 writes code into them. Both are needed;
                                     allow-jit alone is not sufficient for
                                     Electron.

  DELIBERATELY ABSENT — do not add without a specific reason:

    com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation
      Only needed to load unsigned third-party native modules. Everything we
      ship is signed by the same team, and this entitlement is a real weakening
      of the runtime, so it stays off until a concrete dlopen actually fails.

    com.apple.security.cs.allow-dyld-environment-variables
      Same story — a debugging convenience that widens the attack surface.

    com.apple.security.app-sandbox
      This is a Developer ID build for direct distribution, NOT the Mac App
      Store. The App Sandbox would break the embedded loopback HTTP server the
      whole shell runs on (design §2.2).
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
	<true/>
	<key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
	<true/>
</dict>
</plist>
